SIMPLE: marl
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Marl
<hw>Marl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Marline</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To cover, as part of a
rope, with marline, marking a peculiar hitch at each turn to prevent
unwinding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marling spike</b></col>. <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Marline</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Marl
<hw>Marl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>marle</ets>, F.
<ets>marne</ets>, LL. <ets>margila</ets>, dim. of L. <ets>marga</ets>
marl. Originally a Celtic word, according to Pliny, xvii. 7: ⟦ldquo⟧Quod
genus terrae Galli et Britanni <ets>margam</ets> vocant.⟦rdquo⟧
⟦root⟧274.]</ety> <def>A mixed earthy substance, consisting of carbonate
of lime, clay, and sand, in very variable proportions, and accordingly
designated as calcareous, clayey, or sandy. See
<er>Greensand</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Marl
<hw>Marl</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Marled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Marling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>marner</ets>. See
<er>Marl</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To overspread or manure with
marl; <as>as, to <ex>marl</ex> a field</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marlaceous</ent>⟦br⟧
